{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17418517","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17418517"},"attributes":{"position":1,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T10:36:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T10:36:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261521"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261521"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12663"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516600","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516600"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:44:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:44:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12663"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261521","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261521"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T10:36:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:37:56+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":5,"questionsAnswered":5,"marksTotal":5,"marksAttainable":5,"marksAttempted":5,"finishedAt":null,"resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.4,"questionsCorrect":2,"marksCorrect":2},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"12663","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12663"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.08,0.84,0.01,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5136"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103130"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5136","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5136"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12663"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85591"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"359"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8627"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9431"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36477"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36531"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42796"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103130","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103130"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 39-year-old man presents to general practice with complaints of shortness of breath, chest pain, and palpitations during exercise over the past 6 months. He has no medical history and does not take any prescribed medications regularly. He does not smoke but drinks wine occasionally. Family history reveals the sudden cardiac death of his elder brother at age 32.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn physical examination, his blood pressure is 130/80 mmHg, pulse 84/min temperature 37.0\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC and respiratory rate 14/min. Chest auscultation reveals clear lungs, dual heart sounds with an added fourth heart sound and harsh crescendo-decrescendo systolic ejection murmur. The murmur is best heard between the apex and left sternal border and radiates to the suprasternal notch which increases in intensity while standing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn ECG shows (image)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cardiac MRI","Troponin and BNP levels","Echocardiography","Cardiac catheterisation","Stress ECG"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s presentation and ECG are consistent with hypertrophic obstructive cardiomyopathy (HOCM), which is a genetic heart muscle disease caused by a mutation in sarcomere protein genes. It is characterised by left ventricular hypertrophy, causing\u00a0left ventricular outflow obstruction, diastolic dysfunction, myocardial ischaemia, and systolic anterior motion of the mitral valve.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next investigation in this patient is \u003Cstrong\u003Eechocardiography\u003C/strong\u003E, a non-invasive diagnostic test. It is the main diagnostic tool for assessing the structure and function of the heart, including the thickness and movement of the heart walls, and any valvular disorder, such as mitral regurgitation or aortic stenosis. Serial echocardiographic evaluations are recommended to monitor disease progression and guide treatment choices for patients with HOCM.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiac MRI (cMRI) \u003C/strong\u003Eis a noninvasive imaging technique. While it provides more information than echocardiography, echocardiography remains the first-line diagnostic investigation. Given the expense associated with cMRI, it is reserved for cases where a diagnosis of HOCM remains uncertain after echocardiography.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETroponin and BNP levels \u003C/strong\u003Ehave no role in the diagnosis of HOCM. They are proteins that are released into the bloodstream when there is damage to the heart muscle, such as after a myocardial infarction. However, in this case, the patient\u0027s symptoms and physical examination findings suggest valvular or structural heart disease, which may not be reflected in the levels of troponin on BNP. Troponin testing is important for the evaluation of acute chest pain. However, this patient has no chest pain at present. Hence, this is not required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiac catheterisation \u003C/strong\u003Eis an invasive diagnostic test for coronary artery disease. While not essential for diagnosing HOCM, it is beneficial in assessing the extent of outflow obstruction, cardiac hemodynamics, and, notably, coronary anatomy. This procedure is particularly helpful when considering invasive therapeutic options, such as pacemaker implantation or cardiac surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStress ECG \u003C/strong\u003Einvolves monitoring ECG while the patient exercises on a treadmill or stationary bike. It is useful for assessing the patient\u0027s cardiovascular fitness and can help identify any abnormalities in the heart\u0027s response to exercise. However, it is less specific and sensitive than echocardiography for diagnosing valvular or structural heart disease. This might even be contraindicated for HOCM with severe LV outflow tract obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Echocardiography is an invaluable tool in the diagnosis and monitoring of patients with HOCM."],"references":["Maron BJ. Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy: a systematic review. JAMA. 2002 Mar 13. 287(10):1308-20.","Basit H, Brito D, Sharma S. Hypertrophic Cardiomyopathy. [Updated 2022 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85591"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12663"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20305"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20305","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20305"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/rM26uesGnrrsO2s5OkeLIaDlUt